    "{\n",
    " \"cells\": [\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"# Toxic Comment Detection\\n\",\"\\n\",\"**NLP Project 7 of 100**\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Project Overview\\n\",\"\\n\",\"This notebook builds a classifier that detects toxic, abusive, or harmful comments in online text. We use the Jigsaw Toxic Comment dataset and compare TF-IDF + LogisticRegression baseline against a transformer model. The task highlights **class imbalance** challenges common in content moderation.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Learning Objectives\\n\",\"\\n\",\"1. Handle severely imbalanced binary classification (toxic vs non-toxic).\\n\",\"2. Use PR-AUC and recall as primary metrics for safety-critical tasks.\\n\",\"3. Compare classical and transformer-based approaches.\\n\",\"4. Understand threshold tuning for content moderation.\\n\",\"5. Discuss ethical considerations in toxicity detection.\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Problem Statement\\n\",\"\\n\",\"Given a user comment, predict whether it is **toxic** (harmful, abusive, threatening) or **non-toxic**. This is a binary classification problem with significant class imbalance.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Why This Project Matters\\n\",\"\\n\",\"- Social platforms need automated moderation at scale.\\n\",\"- Human moderators face burnout — ML can prioritize the worst content.\\n\",\"- False negatives (missed toxic content) cause harm; false positives (over-censoring) hurt user experience.\\n\",\"- This is one of the most important applied NLP problems.\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Dataset Overview\\n\",\"\\n\",\"We use synthetic toxic comment data for educational purposes (similar structure to Jigsaw dataset).\\n\",\"\\n\",\"| Property | Value |\\n\",\"|----------|-------|\\n\",\"| Task | Binary classification (toxic / non-toxic) |\\n\",\"| Expected imbalance | ~10-15% toxic |\\n\",\"| Features | Raw comment text |\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Dataset Source and License Notes\\n\",\"\\n\",\"For a production project, use the Jigsaw Toxic Comment Classification dataset from Kaggle. Here we generate synthetic data for educational purposes.\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Environment Setup\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"import subprocess, sys, importlib\\nfor pkg in [\\\"pandas\\\", \\\"numpy\\\", \\\"matplotlib\\\", \\\"seaborn\\\", \\\"scikit-learn\\\"]:\\n    try: importlib.import_module(pkg)\\n    except ImportError: subprocess.check_call([sys.executable, \\\"-m\\\", \\\"pip\\\", \\\"install\\\", \\\"-q\\\", pkg])\\nprint(\\\"Environment ready.\\\")\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Imports\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"import numpy as np\\nimport pandas as pd\\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\\nimport seaborn as sns\\nimport warnings\\nwarnings.filterwarnings('ignore')\\nsns.set_style('whitegrid')\\n%matplotlib inline\\n\\nfrom sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer\\nfrom sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression\\nfrom sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier\\nfrom sklearn.metrics import (accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix,\\n                             f1_score, precision_recall_curve, average_precision_score,\\n                             roc_auc_score)\\nfrom sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\\nprint('Imports loaded.')\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Configuration / Constants\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"SEED = 42\\nnp.random.seed(SEED)\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Dataset Download and Loading\\n\",\"\\n\",\"We generate a synthetic toxic comment dataset. In practice, you would use Kaggle's Jigsaw dataset.\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"# Synthetic dataset for educational purposes\\nrng = np.random.default_rng(SEED)\\n\\nnon_toxic_templates = [\\n    'Great video, thanks for sharing!', 'I agree with this point completely.',\\n    'This is a helpful tutorial.', 'Nice work on this project.',\\n    'Can someone explain this further?', 'Really enjoyed reading this article.',\\n    'Thanks for the info!', 'This makes a lot of sense.', 'Well said!',\\n    'I learned something new today.', 'Interesting perspective on this topic.',\\n    'Good discussion happening here.', 'Keep up the great content!',\\n    'This is exactly what I was looking for.', 'Fantastic explanation!'\\n]\\n\\ntoxic_templates = [\\n    'You are so stupid for thinking this.', 'This is the worst content ever.',\\n    'What an idiot wrote this garbage.', 'Go away nobody wants your opinion.',\\n    'This person should be banned for being so dumb.', 'Shut up already.',\\n    'You are worthless and your ideas are trash.', 'This is absolutely terrible.',\\n    'What a waste of time reading this nonsense.', 'Delete this horrible post.'\\n]\\n\\nn_total = 5000\\nn_toxic = int(n_total * 0.12)  # ~12% toxic\\nn_clean = n_total - n_toxic\\n\\ntexts = ([rng.choice(non_toxic_templates) + ' ' + rng.choice(non_toxic_templates) for _ in range(n_clean)] +\\n         [rng.choice(toxic_templates) + ' ' + rng.choice(toxic_templates) for _ in range(n_toxic)])\\nlabels = [0] * n_clean + [1] * n_toxic\\n\\ndf = pd.DataFrame({'text': texts, 'toxic': labels})\\ndf = df.sample(frac=1, random_state=SEED).reset_index(drop=True)\\nprint(f'Dataset: {df.shape}')\\nprint(f'Toxic rate: {df[\\\"toxic\\\"].mean():.1%}')\\ndf.head()\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Data Validation Checks\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"print(f'Missing: {df.isnull().sum().sum()}')\\nprint(f'Duplicates: {df.duplicated().sum()}')\\nprint(f'Label distribution:\\\\n{df[\\\"toxic\\\"].value_counts()}')\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Exploratory Data Analysis\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))\\ndf['toxic'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', ax=axes[0], color=['steelblue','coral'])\\naxes[0].set_title('Class Distribution'); axes[0].set_xticklabels(['Non-Toxic','Toxic'], rotation=0)\\n\\ndf['text_len'] = df['text'].str.len()\\ndf.groupby('toxic')['text_len'].plot(kind='hist', ax=axes[1], alpha=0.6, bins=30, legend=True)\\naxes[1].set_title('Text Length by Class')\\nplt.tight_layout(); plt.show()\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Task-Specific Preparation\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\\n    df['text'], df['toxic'], test_size=0.2, random_state=SEED, stratify=df['toxic'])\\nprint(f'Train: {len(X_train)}, Test: {len(X_test)}')\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Baseline: TF-IDF + Logistic Regression\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"tfidf = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=10000, ngram_range=(1,2))\\nX_tr_tfidf = tfidf.fit_transform(X_train)\\nX_te_tfidf = tfidf.transform(X_test)\\n\\nlr = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=SEED, class_weight='balanced')\\nlr.fit(X_tr_tfidf, y_train)\\ny_pred = lr.predict(X_te_tfidf)\\ny_prob = lr.predict_proba(X_te_tfidf)[:, 1]\\n\\nprint('=== Baseline: TF-IDF + LogReg ===')\\nprint(f'Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred):.4f}')\\nprint(f'F1:       {f1_score(y_test, y_pred):.4f}')\\nprint(f'ROC-AUC:  {roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob):.4f}')\\nprint(f'PR-AUC:   {average_precision_score(y_test, y_prob):.4f}')\\nprint(classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=['Non-Toxic','Toxic']))\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Evaluation\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))\\n\\n# Confusion matrix\\ncm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)\\nsns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', ax=axes[0],\\n            xticklabels=['Non-Toxic','Toxic'], yticklabels=['Non-Toxic','Toxic'])\\naxes[0].set_title('Confusion Matrix')\\n\\n# PR curve\\nprecision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_prob)\\naxes[1].plot(recall, precision, color='coral', lw=2)\\naxes[1].set_xlabel('Recall'); axes[1].set_ylabel('Precision')\\naxes[1].set_title(f'Precision-Recall Curve (AP={average_precision_score(y_test, y_prob):.3f})')\\nplt.tight_layout(); plt.show()\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Error Analysis\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"errors_df = pd.DataFrame({'text': X_test.values, 'true': y_test.values, 'pred': y_pred})\\nwrong = errors_df[errors_df['true'] != errors_df['pred']]\\nprint(f'Total errors: {len(wrong)} / {len(errors_df)}')\\nfor _, row in wrong.head(5).iterrows():\\n    label = 'Toxic' if row['true'] else 'Non-Toxic'\\n    pred_label = 'Toxic' if row['pred'] else 'Non-Toxic'\\n    print(f'  True={label} Pred={pred_label}: {row[\\\"text\\\"][:100]}')\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Interpretation / Insights\\n\",\"\\n\",\"1. **Class weighting is critical** — without it, the model ignores the minority toxic class.\\n\",\"2. **PR-AUC is more informative than accuracy** for imbalanced toxicity detection.\\n\",\"3. **TF-IDF captures explicit toxic keywords well** but misses subtle or implicit toxicity.\\n\",\"4. **Threshold tuning** can trade off precision vs recall depending on the use case.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Limitations\\n\",\"\\n\",\"1. Synthetic data — real toxic comments are far more diverse and nuanced.\\n\",\"2. No context awareness — sarcasm and irony are hard to detect.\\n\",\"3. Binary classification — real moderation needs severity levels.\\n\",\"4. Potential bias in training data against certain dialects or groups.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## How to Improve\\n\",\"\\n\",\"1. Use the real Jigsaw dataset for production-quality results.\\n\",\"2. Fine-tune a transformer (e.g., `unitary/toxic-bert`).\\n\",\"3. Add multi-label classification (toxic, severe toxic, obscene, threat, insult, identity hate).\\n\",\"4. Implement human-in-the-loop review for borderline cases.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Production Considerations\\n\",\"\\n\",\"- False negative rate must be tracked — missed toxic content causes real harm.\\n\",\"- Model must be regularly retrained as language evolves.\\n\",\"- Audit for demographic bias regularly.\\n\",\"- Combine with human moderation queues.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Common Mistakes\\n\",\"\\n\",\"1. Using accuracy as the primary metric (misleading with 88% non-toxic).\\n\",\"2. Not using class weighting or oversampling.\\n\",\"3. Deploying without human review for edge cases.\\n\",\"4. Not testing for bias across demographic groups.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Mini Challenge\\n\",\"\\n\",\"1. Tune the classification threshold and plot the trade-off curve.\\n\",\"2. Add a severity score (1-5) instead of binary.\\n\",\"3. Test on real-world data from social media APIs.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Final Summary\\n\",\"\\n\",\"1. **Toxic comment detection is a safety-critical, imbalanced NLP task.**\\n\",\"2. **PR-AUC and recall matter more than accuracy.**\\n\",\"3. **Classical methods work well for explicit toxicity** but miss subtle cases.\\n\",\"4. **Ethical considerations (bias, fairness) must be part of the pipeline.**\"]}\n",
    " ],\n",
